iStock Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Kinshasa - Christian sect members stormed a prison in the Democratic Republic of Congo's capital on Wednesday, freeing the leader of their movement and 50 others, DRC's justice minister said.Bundu dia Kongo movement leader Ne Mwanda Nsemi is now on the run after a 04:00 attack on the prison in Kinshasa, Justice Minister Alexis Thambwe Mwamba told local radio station TOP CONGO FM.Gunfire could be heard in the morning, but the justice minister said the situation is now under control."Security force members who were sent as reinforcements have entered the prison," he said. "Ne Mwanda Nsemi is on the run, but we will soon get our hands on him."Ne Mwanda Nsemi was arrested in March, along with many followers, after clashes between them and police. He has a strong following in southwestern DRC.Ne Mwanda Nsemi has led the sect since 1986. The group says it seeks the rehabilitation of the pre-colonial Kongo kingdom. Clashes between the sect and police in 2008 saw hundreds killed in Bas-Congo province.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.